# Testing Strategy Defaults

Use this rule for the **mechanics** of testing: framework, runtime, markers, and layer boundaries. Whether to write a given test at all is a separate decision — see `testing_when_to_write.mdc`. For the TDD workflow once a test is justified, see `tdd_business_logic_non_ui.mdc`.

## Framework and runtime

- Use `pytest` as the default framework.
- Tests run through FreeCAD AppRun via `run_tests.py`, using the real PySide2 runtime.
- Use `unittest.mock` only for unit-level isolation boundaries; do not mock collaborators that you own.

## Marker taxonomy

Follow the markers defined in `pyproject.toml`:

- `unit` — fast, in-process, no subprocess or real network.
- `integration` — cross-module, real subprocess/filesystem/protocol behavior.
- `runtime_parity` — tied to FreeCAD AppRun behavior; must fail with actionable diagnostics or skip clearly when prerequisites are missing.
- `manual_acceptance` — broad UI workflow validation lives in `docs/ACCEPTANCE_TESTS.md`, not in pytest.

## Layering expectations

- Unit tests cover business logic and explicit contracts.
- Integration tests cover editor/runner boundaries, subprocess lifecycle, stdout/stderr, exit codes, and run logs.
- Broad UI workflow validation stays manual via `docs/ACCEPTANCE_TESTS.md` unless the user explicitly requests UI automation.
- An "integration" test that mocks out the integration boundary is really a unit test — put it under `tests/unit/`.

## Scope discipline

- During setup-only requests, scaffold config/docs/directories without writing speculative test cases.
- Never add a test purely to raise coverage. Coverage is not a goal; signal is.
